1
00:01:39,520 --> 00:01:41,400
How many times
are we going to keep doing this?

2
00:01:41,480 --> 00:01:44,000
We keep running it
until the hybrid holds.

3
00:01:44,080 --> 00:01:46,160
<i>We are on security level five.</i>

4
00:01:46,240 --> 00:01:48,600
The deregs took.
No sign of rejection.

5
00:01:49,360 --> 00:01:51,400
There's still mutations
in genome seven.

6
00:01:51,680 --> 00:01:52,720
Thank you.

7
00:01:52,800 --> 00:01:56,680
<i>All genetic waste must be taken
to the cremation chamber by 5:00 p.m.</i>

8
00:01:58,200 --> 00:02:00,080
<i>Tank 12 is offline</i>

9
00:02:00,160 --> 00:02:02,200
<i>until genetic modification
stabilizes.</i>

10
00:02:08,240 --> 00:02:09,960
All right. Let's get this over with.

11
00:02:10,040 --> 00:02:11,320
Here we go.

12
00:02:13,720 --> 00:02:16,000
Oh, yeah. Sorry. Hold on.

13
00:02:18,320 --> 00:02:19,680
Okay. Yeah.

14
00:02:23,800 --> 00:02:26,040
Three, two, one.

15
00:02:30,840 --> 00:02:33,160
<i>Step up here.
Waiting for authorization.</i>

16
00:02:34,880 --> 00:02:38,600
I didn't see the labs,
but I assume we upped the soporifics?

17
00:02:39,040 --> 00:02:40,600
Yeah, I'm gonna have to go as high

18
00:02:40,680 --> 00:02:42,320
as 0.5 milliliters
per hundred pounds.

19
00:02:42,800 --> 00:02:44,320
<i>Okay, guys. You're clear.</i>

20
00:02:46,000 --> 00:02:48,000
Well, we don't want
to kill the thing.

21
00:02:48,680 --> 00:02:49,680
Some days I do.

22
00:02:52,920 --> 00:02:54,360
Oh, god.

23
00:02:54,440 --> 00:02:55,840
<i>Tank 12 is offline</i>

24
00:02:55,920 --> 00:02:58,280
<i>until genetic modification
stabilizes.</i>

25
00:03:17,840 --> 00:03:19,360
<i>Alert. Containment failure.</i>

26
00:03:20,400 --> 00:03:22,960
- Hey, what's going on?
<i>- Alert. Containment failure.</i>

27
00:03:24,280 --> 00:03:26,160
<i>Alert. Containment failure.</i>

28
00:03:28,640 --> 00:03:30,000
Oh, god. It's loose!

29
00:03:33,560 --> 00:03:35,720
Run! Containment is locking down!

30
00:03:37,080 --> 00:03:39,400
- The D-Rex broke free!
- We got to get out of here!

31
00:03:39,480 --> 00:03:40,800
Seal the doors!

32
00:03:40,880 --> 00:03:41,880
Seal the doors!

33
00:03:44,440 --> 00:03:45,480
We got to get out of here!

34
00:03:45,560 --> 00:03:48,200
- Come on! Go... go!
- DeSanto! The door!

35
00:03:48,280 --> 00:03:49,800
Oh, god. Oh, god.

36
00:03:49,880 --> 00:03:52,400
Oh, no! No... no! No... no! Come on!

37
00:03:52,480 --> 00:03:53,760
No... no! No!

38
00:03:53,840 --> 00:03:55,296
- Okay, it's just...
- No... no! It's okay.

39
00:03:55,320 --> 00:03:56,736
- Come on. Come on!
- Just stick... Get the key in.

40
00:03:56,760 --> 00:03:58,800
Three, two, one.

41
00:04:00,960 --> 00:04:02,840
Come on! Three, two...

42
00:04:02,920 --> 00:04:04,000
Come on!

43
00:04:10,000 --> 00:04:11,760
Come on! Open the door!

44
00:04:12,160 --> 00:04:13,160
Please!

45
00:04:16,480 --> 00:04:18,600
Please? Okay, just turn the key.

46
00:04:18,680 --> 00:04:20,320
It's fine. It's... it's okay.

47
00:04:20,400 --> 00:04:22,160
Just turn the key. Just turn...

48
00:04:22,240 --> 00:04:24,440
- Yeah. Just please open the door.
- I'm sorry.

49
00:04:24,760 --> 00:04:28,160
Please open the door for me!

50
00:04:28,560 --> 00:04:29,600
No!

51
00:04:34,680 --> 00:04:36,320
Oh, god, no.

52
00:04:40,080 --> 00:04:41,960
No! Oh, no!

53
00:04:42,320 --> 00:04:43,760
I'm sorry!

54
00:04:43,840 --> 00:04:46,640
Oh, no!

55
00:05:42,560 --> 00:05:44,120
Come on, what is this?

56
00:05:44,200 --> 00:05:46,776
These things were supposed to be
completely cleared two years ago.

57
00:05:46,800 --> 00:05:48,840
Yeah, well,
I'm not happy about it either, man.

58
00:05:48,920 --> 00:05:50,336
They're trying
to get him up right now.

59
00:05:50,360 --> 00:05:52,160
I don't know what you want me
to tell you.

60
00:05:52,240 --> 00:05:54,120
What does the mayor do,
sit on his ass all day?

61
00:05:54,200 --> 00:05:55,520
It weighs 40 tons, buddy.

62
00:05:55,600 --> 00:05:56,760
Do you want to move it?

63
00:05:59,560 --> 00:06:01,040
<i>out of Manhattan.</i>

64
00:06:01,120 --> 00:06:04,160
<i>The cause of the jam
is none other than Bronto Billy</i>

65
00:06:04,240 --> 00:06:07,560
<i>thought to be the last surviving
sauropod in North America.</i>

66
00:06:07,920 --> 00:06:09,480
<i>- Back to you, Bob.
- Thanks, Hailey.</i>

67
00:06:09,560 --> 00:06:13,200
<i>So, yeah, the aging brachiosaur,
known to be in poor health</i>

68
00:06:13,280 --> 00:06:15,360
<i>broke out
of the Cobble Hill Park enclosure</i>

69
00:06:15,440 --> 00:06:17,760
<i>where it had been living
while receiving medical attention.</i>

70
00:06:30,880 --> 00:06:32,280
Oh, for God's sake.

71
00:06:32,720 --> 00:06:34,880
Rest in peace already,
but get the hell out of the way.

72
00:06:35,720 --> 00:06:37,520
- Damn, that's cold.
- Jeez.

73
00:06:37,600 --> 00:06:40,240
I mean, even for New York,
it's pretty cold.

74
00:06:43,360 --> 00:06:44,960
Miss Bennett, I presume?

75
00:06:45,040 --> 00:06:46,040
Hello.

76
00:06:46,560 --> 00:06:48,400
Weren't we supposed to meet at the...

77
00:06:48,480 --> 00:06:49,960
You're not exactly hard to follow.

78
00:06:51,600 --> 00:06:55,160
- So, how did you hear about me?
- Paulo Pasolini, Blackwater.

79
00:06:55,840 --> 00:06:57,200
Does he have a message for me?

80
00:06:57,280 --> 00:07:00,840
Yes. He said to say,
"Felix isn't himself today."

81
00:07:01,960 --> 00:07:03,040
Okay, I'm listening.

82
00:07:03,120 --> 00:07:05,280
Is that some spy stuff?
'Cause that is fantastic.

83
00:07:07,360 --> 00:07:09,040
What is it that you do
at ParkerGenix?

84
00:07:09,320 --> 00:07:12,080
My company is developing
a new medication

85
00:07:12,160 --> 00:07:14,120
and we have certain needs.

86
00:07:14,200 --> 00:07:17,080
That sounds vague.
And what does that mean in this case?

87
00:07:17,160 --> 00:07:18,720
They say you're good
at procuring things

88
00:07:18,760 --> 00:07:20,280
and not asking a lot of questions.

89
00:07:21,000 --> 00:07:22,000
Do they?

90
00:07:22,080 --> 00:07:23,440
They also say you're untroubled

91
00:07:23,520 --> 00:07:26,280
by possible legal
or ethical implications.

92
00:07:27,560 --> 00:07:29,400
Well, they need to shut up.

93
00:07:29,480 --> 00:07:30,720
Well, take it as a compliment.

94
00:07:30,800 --> 00:07:32,480
Means you get the job done.

95
00:07:33,800 --> 00:07:37,280
I lost a friend on my last job,
so I am not up for procurement.

96
00:07:37,360 --> 00:07:38,696
Well, you don't know what it is yet.

97
00:07:38,720 --> 00:07:40,736
Yes, but you work
for a pharmaceutical company, right?

98
00:07:40,760 --> 00:07:42,440
So... You called me.

99
00:07:42,520 --> 00:07:44,160
I'm spec ops, so it's covert.

100
00:07:44,880 --> 00:07:47,040
I'm guessing info theft?

101
00:07:47,560 --> 00:07:51,400
I... I'm sorry, I do retrieval
and extractions, not heists.

102
00:07:51,840 --> 00:07:53,120
It's dinosaurs.

103
00:07:53,400 --> 00:07:55,920
They may be through with us,
but we're not through with them.

104
00:07:56,280 --> 00:07:57,640
Well, they are all...

105
00:07:58,080 --> 00:07:59,480
They're all dead or dying, so...

106
00:07:59,560 --> 00:08:02,160
Except for on a few islands
around the equator.

107
00:08:02,680 --> 00:08:05,280
Yes, and those are no-go zones
for a reason.

108
00:08:05,800 --> 00:08:06,840
You go there, you die.

109
00:08:07,440 --> 00:08:09,040
Which is where you come in.

110
00:08:11,800 --> 00:08:12,800
No, thanks.

111
00:08:15,200 --> 00:08:16,200
Ms. Bennett!

112
00:08:16,600 --> 00:08:18,480
Did you know that 20%
of the world's population

113
00:08:18,560 --> 00:08:19,720
will die of heart disease?

114
00:08:19,800 --> 00:08:21,920
That's one in every five people
on the planet.

115
00:08:22,000 --> 00:08:23,816
Now, just imagine.
Take somebody you know, anybody

116
00:08:23,840 --> 00:08:25,656
and imagine that you
could be the one to give them

117
00:08:25,680 --> 00:08:27,416
- an extra 20 years of life.
- That's very touching.

118
00:08:27,440 --> 00:08:30,160
- It's not my field, though.
- And we have very deep pockets.

119
00:08:37,640 --> 00:08:38,680
How deep?

120
00:08:39,800 --> 00:08:41,000
For you, extremely.

121
00:08:41,840 --> 00:08:42,840
Well...

122
00:08:44,000 --> 00:08:45,160
I'm gonna need a number.

123
00:08:45,720 --> 00:08:47,400
Ten, six zeros.

124
00:08:48,920 --> 00:08:50,680
Including the one that's in the ten?

125
00:08:51,040 --> 00:08:52,040
No.

126
00:08:53,160 --> 00:08:54,520
It's a fortune, Ms. Bennett.

127
00:08:55,560 --> 00:08:57,456
The kind of money that would mean
you'd never have to put your life

128
00:08:57,480 --> 00:08:58,760
on the line ever again.

129
00:09:01,040 --> 00:09:02,200
All right, what's the hitch?

130
00:09:03,960 --> 00:09:05,560
Possible criminal charges.

131
00:09:05,920 --> 00:09:07,360
We are going to a place

132
00:09:07,440 --> 00:09:10,880
where every government on the planet
has outlawed travel.

133
00:09:13,080 --> 00:09:14,560
Well, we better not
tell anyone, then.

134
00:09:17,880 --> 00:09:19,320
Yeah, that might be a problem.

135
00:09:19,840 --> 00:09:23,560
He doesn't know it yet,
but we're bringing a civilian.

136
00:09:27,960 --> 00:09:31,840
<i>The Neo-Jurassic Age
has proven lethal to Dinosauria.</i>

137
00:09:32,680 --> 00:09:34,680
<i>Though some species can survive</i>

138
00:09:34,760 --> 00:09:38,400
<i>in a few isolated oxygen-rich
tropical microclimates</i>

139
00:09:38,480 --> 00:09:40,560
<i>clustered in equatorial regions</i>

140
00:09:40,800 --> 00:09:42,480
<i>where interactions with humans</i>

141
00:09:42,560 --> 00:09:45,400
<i>and other incompatible
modern species is...</i>

142
00:09:52,240 --> 00:09:53,720
Banner coming down.

143
00:09:55,760 --> 00:09:57,720
Okay, so this is the left metacarpal?

144
00:09:57,800 --> 00:09:58,880
Yeah.

145
00:10:02,920 --> 00:10:04,120
Good morning, Doctor.

146
00:10:04,520 --> 00:10:06,000
Sorry to drop in unannounced.

147
00:10:06,360 --> 00:10:07,480
Can we have a word?

148
00:10:07,560 --> 00:10:09,040
Sorry, it's a hell of a day here.

149
00:10:09,120 --> 00:10:10,120
They're closing us down.

150
00:10:10,560 --> 00:10:12,320
Dr. Henry Loomis, Zora Bennett

151
00:10:12,400 --> 00:10:13,720
- our mission specialist.
- Hello.

152
00:10:13,880 --> 00:10:14,880
Sorry, what mission?

153
00:10:17,280 --> 00:10:20,360
Guys, why don't you just take a break
for a minute, okay?

154
00:10:21,880 --> 00:10:22,880
Thanks, guys.

155
00:10:22,960 --> 00:10:24,840
Dr. Loomis has been
advising ParkerGenix

156
00:10:24,920 --> 00:10:26,880
for the past six months
on paleo-coronary health.

157
00:10:26,960 --> 00:10:28,920
We're developing a new drug,
Paleodioxin

158
00:10:29,000 --> 00:10:31,160
derived from the largest
dinosaur species on record.

159
00:10:31,640 --> 00:10:34,560
Computer modeling suggests
it could forestall coronary disease

160
00:10:34,640 --> 00:10:36,200
by an average of two decades.

161
00:10:36,280 --> 00:10:38,096
Think what that might have meant
for your mother.

162
00:10:38,120 --> 00:10:40,440
- I'm so sorry for your loss.
- Okay.

163
00:10:40,520 --> 00:10:43,120
Anybody can read a file.
If you get personal, though, I'm out.

164
00:10:43,200 --> 00:10:44,480
I'm sorry for overstepping.

165
00:10:45,040 --> 00:10:48,760
This research is crucial.
We just can't get it to trial.

166
00:10:48,840 --> 00:10:50,560
We're unable to synthesize the DNA

167
00:10:50,640 --> 00:10:52,960
so we need samples
from living dinosaurs.

168
00:10:53,040 --> 00:10:55,600
And the species must be
a true colossus.

169
00:10:56,080 --> 00:10:58,040
It's the biggest animals
across three categories:

170
00:10:58,120 --> 00:11:00,240
Seagoing, land-based, and avian.

171
00:11:00,880 --> 00:11:02,520
Why the biggest?

172
00:11:02,880 --> 00:11:04,040
Oh, it's their hearts.

173
00:11:04,440 --> 00:11:06,880
The bigger they were,
the bigger their coronary muscles.

174
00:11:07,200 --> 00:11:08,440
And they lived the longest

175
00:11:08,880 --> 00:11:12,080
over a hundred years
for some Cretaceous-era sauropods.

176
00:11:12,480 --> 00:11:16,040
Which means
the three dinosaurs they need are

177
00:11:16,880 --> 00:11:21,080
Mosasaurus, which lives in the ocean

178
00:11:22,400 --> 00:11:24,720
and Titanosaurus.

179
00:11:25,280 --> 00:11:27,080
You'll find them on land.

180
00:11:29,120 --> 00:11:32,760
And in the sky, Quetzalcoatlus.

181
00:11:33,080 --> 00:11:34,360
It's the largest pterosaur.

182
00:11:35,400 --> 00:11:37,840
Each of them had an average lifespan
of well over a century

183
00:11:37,920 --> 00:11:39,240
even before DNA refinement.

184
00:11:39,760 --> 00:11:41,520
A drug that could prevent
heart disease

185
00:11:41,600 --> 00:11:43,840
would be the biggest
medical breakthrough in centuries.

186
00:11:43,920 --> 00:11:47,120
Yeah. And I'm sure
it'd be worth billions, right?

187
00:11:47,960 --> 00:11:48,960
Trillions.

188
00:11:49,480 --> 00:11:51,840
The only way for our scientists
to complete the strands now

189
00:11:51,920 --> 00:11:55,360
is with blood and tissue samples
from living dinosaurs.

190
00:11:56,600 --> 00:11:58,440
Wait. You want to take blood samples

191
00:11:58,520 --> 00:12:00,080
from these animals
while they're alive?

192
00:12:00,160 --> 00:12:03,160
Hemoglobin deoxygenates
within seconds postmortem.

193
00:12:03,840 --> 00:12:06,000
Lividity and hypostasis
follow immediately.

194
00:12:07,280 --> 00:12:10,120
Fortunately for us,
all these species exist

195
00:12:10,200 --> 00:12:12,280
in one isolated location.

196
00:12:12,360 --> 00:12:15,200
We're putting together a team,
and we'd like to leave immediately.

197
00:12:15,720 --> 00:12:16,720
We have competitors

198
00:12:16,800 --> 00:12:19,160
and Mr. Parker does not
tolerate second place.

199
00:12:19,680 --> 00:12:20,760
Can you be ready tomorrow?

200
00:12:21,560 --> 00:12:22,560
Dr. Loomis?

201
00:12:25,120 --> 00:12:26,400
I thought I was just advising.

202
00:12:26,480 --> 00:12:27,960
You are. In person.

203
00:12:28,760 --> 00:12:30,640
We're not qualified
to identify the animals

204
00:12:30,720 --> 00:12:31,920
or predict behavior.

205
00:12:32,560 --> 00:12:33,560
Well...

206
00:12:35,440 --> 00:12:36,640
Why don't you send an army?

207
00:12:37,640 --> 00:12:38,680
You're a rich company.

208
00:12:38,760 --> 00:12:40,120
Confidentiality.

209
00:12:40,680 --> 00:12:42,600
The fewer people
know about this, the better.

210
00:12:43,280 --> 00:12:44,840
I can guarantee your safety.

211
00:12:44,920 --> 00:12:46,520
I mean, you know, more or less.

212
00:12:46,600 --> 00:12:48,696
Oh, no, no. It's not about my safety.
It's just, it's...

213
00:12:48,720 --> 00:12:50,280
- "More or less"?
- Yeah.

214
00:12:54,520 --> 00:12:57,480
What you're proposing
is really illegal.

215
00:12:58,320 --> 00:13:00,200
Oh, did we...
Did you tell him about the zeros?

216
00:13:00,280 --> 00:13:02,760
- That's not gonna work with him.
- What are you talking about?

217
00:13:05,520 --> 00:13:07,240
You ever seen a dinosaur in the wild?

218
00:13:08,760 --> 00:13:10,680
I don't mean in a theme park
when you were a kid

219
00:13:10,760 --> 00:13:14,200
or watching some poor creature
wander around town lost.

220
00:13:14,640 --> 00:13:16,760
I mean, in its natural habitat.

221
00:13:18,200 --> 00:13:20,000
'Cause until you've done that

222
00:13:20,480 --> 00:13:22,120
you're just a guy who visits zoos.

223
00:13:37,120 --> 00:13:39,520
We sold a dozen tickets
all last week.

224
00:13:42,160 --> 00:13:45,000
Five years ago,
you'd have to wait in line for hours

225
00:13:45,080 --> 00:13:46,280
if you could even get in.

226
00:13:49,960 --> 00:13:52,000
Nobody cares about
these animals anymore.

227
00:13:54,440 --> 00:13:55,440
They deserve better.

228
00:13:57,040 --> 00:13:58,560
I just... I need a second.

229
00:13:59,520 --> 00:14:01,000
No, yeah. Take...

230
00:14:01,080 --> 00:14:02,400
Take all the time that you need.

231
00:14:03,280 --> 00:14:05,360
Take all the minutes. Not like

232
00:14:07,280 --> 00:14:11,320
your entire life has been,
you know, leading up to this moment.

233
00:14:30,200 --> 00:14:32,000
- You ready?
- Yeah.

234
00:15:16,960 --> 00:15:18,040
Three in a row!

235
00:15:19,760 --> 00:15:21,000
Captain Kincaid.

236
00:15:23,320 --> 00:15:24,440
Martin Krebs.

237
00:15:25,160 --> 00:15:26,240
We spoke on the phone.

238
00:15:27,600 --> 00:15:30,320
Yeah, Krebs, look, I'm sorry.

239
00:15:31,200 --> 00:15:33,080
I thought it over, and I can't do it.

240
00:15:34,360 --> 00:15:37,400
I'd like to, just as a favor to Zora,
but I can't.

241
00:15:39,360 --> 00:15:40,360
What?

242
00:15:41,320 --> 00:15:43,520
We already agreed on the phone.

243
00:15:44,920 --> 00:15:46,080
You named your price.

244
00:15:46,160 --> 00:15:48,840
It's not that. I just...
It's a little too risky for my boat.

245
00:15:50,680 --> 00:15:53,400
She's not paid off yet,
so I imagine you understand.

246
00:15:53,480 --> 00:15:54,800
No hard feelings, Z.

247
00:15:55,240 --> 00:15:57,800
Hey, two double rums,<i> merci</i>.

248
00:15:58,320 --> 00:15:59,400
What the hell is this?

249
00:15:59,480 --> 00:16:01,000
- He's your guy.
- Yeah.

250
00:16:01,080 --> 00:16:03,240
We spent ten years
in MARSOC together.

251
00:16:03,840 --> 00:16:05,760
Duncan's the best.
Otherwise, I wouldn't be here.

252
00:16:05,960 --> 00:16:07,240
Best at what? Drinking?

253
00:16:07,320 --> 00:16:09,720
Fabrice, not the guns, okay?

254
00:16:10,120 --> 00:16:11,120
All right. Okay.

255
00:16:11,200 --> 00:16:13,520
Moving things and people
in and out of places

256
00:16:13,600 --> 00:16:14,720
they shouldn't be.

257
00:16:15,080 --> 00:16:17,040
Trouble is,
I really can't do it this time, Z.

258
00:16:17,120 --> 00:16:18,240
I'm sorry.

259
00:16:18,320 --> 00:16:19,960
And I'm afraid that's final.

260
00:16:21,280 --> 00:16:23,600
That's a hell of a setback, Duncan.
You promised me.

261
00:16:24,200 --> 00:16:25,520
We're screwed now.

262
00:16:27,920 --> 00:16:28,960
I'm sorry.

263
00:16:29,600 --> 00:16:31,680
I hate to see this
all fall apart on you.

264
00:16:35,000 --> 00:16:36,000
I'll tell you what.

265
00:16:37,040 --> 00:16:39,320
Why don't you make some sort
of good faith gesture?

266
00:16:39,680 --> 00:16:42,560
Like, maybe, you know,
I'm just spitballing here

267
00:16:42,640 --> 00:16:44,640
but maybe you could

268
00:16:44,720 --> 00:16:46,376
double the number
that you and I spoke about

269
00:16:46,400 --> 00:16:48,880
and then, I can take care of Duncan
and his crew out of my end.

270
00:16:49,600 --> 00:16:50,800
Oh, I see.

271
00:16:51,520 --> 00:16:52,600
That's very nice.

272
00:16:52,920 --> 00:16:55,040
You guys cook this up
on the phone or just now?

273
00:16:55,120 --> 00:16:56,640
Oh, I'm just trying to help you out.

274
00:16:57,000 --> 00:16:58,720
I don't have to sit here
and be insulted.

275
00:16:58,800 --> 00:17:01,240
For God's sake, fine. Agreed.

276
00:17:01,320 --> 00:17:03,240
- Great.
- Great.

277
00:17:03,640 --> 00:17:05,280
We'll loop up toward Barbados

278
00:17:06,280 --> 00:17:10,160
to avoid government patrols,
but there aren't many anyway.

279
00:17:12,400 --> 00:17:13,400
Why's that?

280
00:17:17,240 --> 00:17:19,600
No one's dumb enough
to go where we're going.

281
00:17:21,880 --> 00:17:24,160
Hey! Hey!

282
00:17:24,240 --> 00:17:25,280
Come here!

283
00:17:26,680 --> 00:17:27,880
- Hey.
- Hey.

284
00:17:27,960 --> 00:17:29,040
Over here.

285
00:17:29,120 --> 00:17:30,440
- Hey, Z.
- Hi.

286
00:17:30,520 --> 00:17:32,280
- Hey, how you been?
- Oh, good.

287
00:17:32,840 --> 00:17:34,040
Bobby Atwater.

288
00:17:34,120 --> 00:17:35,720
He'll be helping with team security.

289
00:17:35,800 --> 00:17:37,520
Security for...

290
00:17:38,040 --> 00:17:39,720
Make sure you don't end up
in one of these.

291
00:17:45,160 --> 00:17:46,280
A live one.

292
00:17:47,480 --> 00:17:48,840
Is there anything else?

293
00:17:49,480 --> 00:17:51,960
Yeah, listen, I'm not gonna be able
to do this, you know?

294
00:17:52,040 --> 00:17:53,696
I... I would love to,
as a favor for you, Z, but...

295
00:17:53,720 --> 00:17:55,760
- Oh, no, we ran it already.
- All right, cool.

296
00:17:57,760 --> 00:17:58,840
So, when we leaving?

297
00:18:11,280 --> 00:18:12,600
- Hey, LeClerc.
- What?

298
00:18:12,680 --> 00:18:14,240
Did you see how much
Kincaid's paying us

299
00:18:14,280 --> 00:18:15,320
for this one?

300
00:18:16,000 --> 00:18:17,120
Oh, yeah.

301
00:18:17,720 --> 00:18:19,320
- We're in trouble.
- Hell yeah.

302
00:18:25,800 --> 00:18:29,600
Well, the good news is,
the Mosasaur was tagged in captivity

303
00:18:29,680 --> 00:18:32,440
and InGen continued to track it
after its escape.

304
00:18:32,520 --> 00:18:34,216
We bought their data
when they entered Chapter 11

305
00:18:34,240 --> 00:18:35,480
so now we track it.

306
00:18:36,120 --> 00:18:38,000
Nobody else seems to know
much about it.

307
00:18:38,080 --> 00:18:39,080
But

308
00:18:39,560 --> 00:18:41,080
that's it right there.

309
00:18:41,440 --> 00:18:44,440
So, first sample in 150 miles or so.

310
00:18:44,840 --> 00:18:45,960
Very close to the equator.

311
00:18:47,360 --> 00:18:48,840
But why... why near the equator?

312
00:18:48,920 --> 00:18:50,560
Why don't they survive anywhere else?

313
00:18:51,680 --> 00:18:54,080
The fitness landscape of the Earth
no longer suits them.

314
00:18:55,120 --> 00:18:56,360
The air is different.

315
00:18:57,840 --> 00:19:00,360
The solar radiation is different,
the insects, vegetation.

316
00:19:00,440 --> 00:19:01,560
Everything is different.

317
00:19:01,880 --> 00:19:03,000
But close to the equator

318
00:19:03,080 --> 00:19:05,680
it's nearly the climate
of 60 million years ago.

319
00:19:05,760 --> 00:19:07,480
It's warmer and rich with oxygen.

320
00:19:07,560 --> 00:19:11,320
And the Mosasaur generally circles
the island we're headed to.

321
00:19:11,680 --> 00:19:12,840
There's a complex there

322
00:19:12,920 --> 00:19:15,800
that was R and D
for the original park.

323
00:19:16,880 --> 00:19:21,040
It was abandoned after an accident.

324
00:19:23,160 --> 00:19:25,240
We're gonna want to get in,
get our three samples

325
00:19:25,320 --> 00:19:26,920
and get out as quickly as possible.

326
00:19:28,000 --> 00:19:29,600
Because even though
two dozen species

327
00:19:29,680 --> 00:19:32,800
have survived there, alone,
for almost 20 years

328
00:19:34,000 --> 00:19:35,040
make no mistake

329
00:19:35,120 --> 00:19:37,160
this is by no means
a controlled environment.

330
00:19:38,160 --> 00:19:40,160
Yeah, I think we'll be okay.

331
00:19:41,280 --> 00:19:42,280
What are those?

332
00:19:42,960 --> 00:19:44,040
Neurotoxins.

333
00:19:44,840 --> 00:19:45,840
How fast?

334
00:19:46,120 --> 00:19:48,360
Paralysis within a couple of seconds.

335
00:19:48,760 --> 00:19:49,880
And then what?

336
00:19:52,160 --> 00:19:53,440
And then you survive.

337
00:19:59,880 --> 00:20:02,360
Is this the part
where you tell me it's a crime

338
00:20:02,440 --> 00:20:03,760
to kill a dinosaur, Doctor?

339
00:20:03,840 --> 00:20:06,160
No, this is where I tell you
it's a sin to kill a dinosaur.

340
00:20:10,480 --> 00:20:13,600
So, what if it's us or them?

341
00:20:15,200 --> 00:20:18,120
Then we've put ourselves
in a place where we don't belong.

342
00:20:20,000 --> 00:20:22,320
That's kind of our specialty,
Dr. Loomis.

343
00:20:24,520 --> 00:20:26,016
We have no intention
of harming the animals.

344
00:20:26,040 --> 00:20:28,840
Let's just get our samples
and go home.

345
00:20:29,280 --> 00:20:31,280
Gonna lose the light
before we make contact.

346
00:20:31,360 --> 00:20:33,080
We'll make a run first thing
in the morning.

347
00:20:33,960 --> 00:20:35,120
How does extraction work?

348
00:20:35,920 --> 00:20:38,120
These darts collect blood samples.

349
00:20:38,200 --> 00:20:39,480
You get one shot with each.

350
00:20:39,560 --> 00:20:41,400
The Mosa has four inches of hide

351
00:20:41,480 --> 00:20:43,680
so you must be within ten meters
to penetrate.

352
00:20:46,000 --> 00:20:48,240
And it self-ejects
when it reaches capacity.

353
00:20:49,480 --> 00:20:51,760
It should fire
a couple of hundred feet in the air

354
00:20:51,840 --> 00:20:52,920
like a model rocket.

355
00:20:56,360 --> 00:20:59,880
On the day, a parachute will open,
and it will float back down to us.

356
00:21:00,320 --> 00:21:01,440
I'll take the shot.

357
00:21:02,520 --> 00:21:04,120
Remote biopsy darting
is pretty basic.

358
00:21:04,200 --> 00:21:05,240
I'm sure I can handle it.

359
00:21:10,200 --> 00:21:11,320
Let me show you something.

360
00:21:16,000 --> 00:21:18,160
- You feel that spray?
- Yeah.

361
00:21:18,240 --> 00:21:21,240
Now imagine the boat rocking
at 15 to 20 degrees

362
00:21:21,320 --> 00:21:24,000
we're moving at 30 knots,
you got sweat running in your eyes

363
00:21:24,080 --> 00:21:26,520
and you're close enough to look
that thing right in the teeth.

364
00:21:27,080 --> 00:21:28,320
You got this.

365
00:21:34,920 --> 00:21:36,000
Please, be my guest.

366
00:21:36,080 --> 00:21:38,160
Oh, really? If you insist.

367
00:21:45,560 --> 00:21:46,840
I can't take it.

368
00:21:48,880 --> 00:21:50,760
I mean, it's been fun working
with you, Z.

369
00:21:50,840 --> 00:21:51,840
What?

370
00:21:51,920 --> 00:21:53,840
But I think we just found
our new team leader.

371
00:21:55,360 --> 00:21:56,560
No offense.

372
00:21:56,640 --> 00:21:59,800
I mean, I don't know anybody
that could be offended by that.

373
00:21:59,880 --> 00:22:00,960
That's mean.

374
00:22:07,000 --> 00:22:08,280
I heard about Booker.

375
00:22:11,320 --> 00:22:12,400
Yeah.

376
00:22:12,480 --> 00:22:13,600
I'm so sorry.

377
00:22:14,960 --> 00:22:15,960
Yeah.

378
00:22:18,120 --> 00:22:19,280
What job were you on?

379
00:22:21,640 --> 00:22:24,400
Just a simple training mission
in Yemen.

380
00:22:25,680 --> 00:22:27,960
Couldn't have been more basic.
Just a car bomb.

381
00:22:29,440 --> 00:22:30,520
Out of nowhere.

382
00:22:33,440 --> 00:22:34,600
Quick at least.

383
00:22:37,320 --> 00:22:38,360
Not really.

384
00:22:39,160 --> 00:22:40,640
Oh, shit.

385
00:22:42,760 --> 00:22:43,960
He didn't deserve that.

386
00:22:45,920 --> 00:22:46,920
No.

387
00:22:50,960 --> 00:22:52,360
I had to tell his wife.

388
00:22:52,440 --> 00:22:54,360
It was... it was brutal.

389
00:22:54,880 --> 00:22:57,200
- You can't keep this up forever, Z.
- No.

390
00:22:57,280 --> 00:22:58,600
This work

391
00:22:59,760 --> 00:23:01,400
it breaks you eventually.

392
00:23:01,480 --> 00:23:02,960
What do you think
I'm doing down here?

393
00:23:03,760 --> 00:23:06,760
I'm just trying
to, you know, buy my life back.

394
00:23:06,840 --> 00:23:08,840
Oh, really?
I thought you just missed me.

395
00:23:09,240 --> 00:23:10,240
Well...

396
00:23:11,920 --> 00:23:13,600
You know what I actually missed?

397
00:23:15,320 --> 00:23:16,640
My own mother's funeral.

398
00:23:18,800 --> 00:23:20,080
Yeah.

399
00:23:20,160 --> 00:23:21,920
That's terrible, Zora.

400
00:23:22,000 --> 00:23:23,840
- Yeah, yeah.
- No, seriously.

401
00:23:23,920 --> 00:23:26,160
That's, like, the worst thing
I've ever heard anybody do.

402
00:23:26,560 --> 00:23:28,520
Thank you.
That's so supportive of you.

403
00:23:30,440 --> 00:23:31,600
God.

404
00:23:38,400 --> 00:23:40,240
Please tell me
you worked it out with Amelia.

405
00:23:46,240 --> 00:23:47,240
Well...

406
00:23:50,520 --> 00:23:52,520
Whenever we looked
at each other, we just

407
00:23:54,960 --> 00:23:56,480
just saw our little boy.

408
00:24:00,120 --> 00:24:02,720
Easier for us both
just to go at it alone, you know?

409
00:24:12,200 --> 00:24:13,440
We are very pathetic.

410
00:24:15,400 --> 00:24:18,240
All right, what do you say
we stay alive?

411
00:24:18,800 --> 00:24:22,840
And, you know, get rich this time.

412
00:24:24,160 --> 00:24:26,440
Rich is nice, but it won't be enough.

413
00:24:27,680 --> 00:24:28,680
For sure.

414
00:24:28,760 --> 00:24:30,800
Do something that matters
while there's still time.

415
00:24:31,320 --> 00:24:32,360
Okay.

416
00:24:32,680 --> 00:24:34,160
Don't just brush that off. I mean it.

417
00:24:35,160 --> 00:24:36,320
Don't wait, Zora.

418
00:24:37,000 --> 00:24:38,160
Do not wait.

419
00:25:00,520 --> 00:25:01,880
You rationing those, honey?

420
00:25:03,320 --> 00:25:04,720
I'm enjoying them.

421
00:25:06,160 --> 00:25:07,840
It's a long way across the Atlantic.

422
00:25:08,040 --> 00:25:09,600
You're gonna miss them
when you run out.

423
00:25:13,160 --> 00:25:15,120
Can I ask why you have so many
in your pocket?

424
00:25:17,280 --> 00:25:18,360
So she doesn't eat them.

425
00:25:19,040 --> 00:25:20,360
Ah, right.

426
00:25:21,120 --> 00:25:22,280
Hey, honey.

427
00:25:22,360 --> 00:25:24,720
Where's your boyfriend?
It's his turn at the wheel.

428
00:25:24,800 --> 00:25:26,000
Is he coming or what?

429
00:25:26,080 --> 00:25:27,640
I told him.

430
00:25:27,720 --> 00:25:29,280
He's just getting dressed.

431
00:25:30,480 --> 00:25:31,480
Okay.

432
00:25:32,280 --> 00:25:33,480
Okay.

433
00:25:33,560 --> 00:25:34,680
Do you want to practice?

434
00:25:35,080 --> 00:25:36,200
All right.

435
00:25:36,880 --> 00:25:39,560
Remember, okay?
It's just like Dad showed you.

436
00:25:39,640 --> 00:25:41,800
Under, under, around.

437
00:25:41,880 --> 00:25:43,480
You guys ever wish
you had a boring dad?

438
00:25:43,960 --> 00:25:45,040
- We do.
- Yeah.

439
00:25:48,800 --> 00:25:49,960
Finally.

440
00:25:54,360 --> 00:25:55,640
Good evening, Xavier.

441
00:25:56,280 --> 00:25:57,400
What's up?

442
00:25:58,520 --> 00:25:59,520
Six o'clock.

443
00:25:59,800 --> 00:26:01,160
I know.

444
00:26:03,200 --> 00:26:05,160
I was out cold.

445
00:26:05,720 --> 00:26:07,136
- It's... it's your watch.
- Oh, I...

446
00:26:07,160 --> 00:26:08,800
I slept like a baby.

447
00:26:12,000 --> 00:26:13,360
You've... you've got the wheel?

448
00:26:15,400 --> 00:26:18,280
Man, I am so tired.

449
00:26:18,600 --> 00:26:21,360
I'm gonna be honest.
I'd probably conk out at the wheel.

450
00:26:21,440 --> 00:26:23,160
I'll take his shift. It's fine.

451
00:26:23,240 --> 00:26:25,080
No, honey, we've been through this.

452
00:26:25,160 --> 00:26:26,600
You need sleep. I need sleep.

453
00:26:27,160 --> 00:26:29,360
It's your shift, Xavier.
Come on, man.

454
00:26:29,920 --> 00:26:33,200
Reuben, can't we just anchor,
for once?

455
00:26:34,120 --> 00:26:36,280
Use the anchor.
We haven't done that yet.

456
00:26:37,200 --> 00:26:39,400
We only carry 50 meters
of anchor chain.

457
00:26:39,920 --> 00:26:41,760
It's 2,000 meters to the bottom.

458
00:26:45,320 --> 00:26:46,376
Kind of sounds like somebody

459
00:26:46,400 --> 00:26:47,816
should've thought about that
before we left.

460
00:26:47,840 --> 00:26:49,416
Do you have any idea
the weight of two thou...

461
00:26:49,440 --> 00:26:51,040
I built this boat, okay, Xavier?

462
00:26:51,120 --> 00:26:53,096
- I... I know what I'm doing.
- Oh, so you're good.

463
00:26:53,120 --> 00:26:54,376
- You're good on the wheel.
- You know what?

464
00:26:54,400 --> 00:26:56,320
Just grab another hour.
I'm... I'm fine.

465
00:26:56,400 --> 00:26:58,720
- Yes. Perfect. You're the best.
- I... I got it. I'm fine.

466
00:26:58,800 --> 00:26:59,800
Fist bump?

467
00:27:00,000 --> 00:27:01,000
Give me some.

468
00:27:01,080 --> 00:27:02,080
Never mind.

469
00:27:02,760 --> 00:27:05,920
Oh, you got licorice, dude?
I love this stuff.

470
00:27:17,800 --> 00:27:18,880
I didn't say a word.

471
00:27:19,200 --> 00:27:20,520
Not... not one word.

472
00:27:21,080 --> 00:27:22,080
Good.

473
00:27:22,880 --> 00:27:23,880
So don't.

474
00:27:26,560 --> 00:27:28,200
What...
Did... did he even bring a shirt?

475
00:27:28,800 --> 00:27:31,920
Okay, clearly you don't see
the side of him that I see.

476
00:27:32,440 --> 00:27:34,080
- The naked side.
- Hey.

477
00:27:35,560 --> 00:27:36,960
I mean, I...

478
00:27:37,040 --> 00:27:39,120
I guess I'd hoped
it would just be the three of us.

479
00:27:39,840 --> 00:27:41,400
You know, one last hurrah.

480
00:27:42,480 --> 00:27:45,200
I'm going to NYU, not Mongolia.

481
00:27:46,600 --> 00:27:47,800
I know. You're right.

482
00:27:53,760 --> 00:27:54,800
What are those?

483
00:27:57,200 --> 00:27:58,200
Where?

484
00:28:04,120 --> 00:28:06,600
One o'clock. Moving east.

485
00:28:06,680 --> 00:28:08,000
Dolphins?

486
00:28:08,080 --> 00:28:09,240
No.

487
00:28:09,640 --> 00:28:10,840
No fins.

488
00:28:11,720 --> 00:28:12,800
Sails.

489
00:28:21,440 --> 00:28:23,240
Bella, grab the wheel.

490
00:28:32,800 --> 00:28:33,800
Left... left.

491
00:28:42,000 --> 00:28:43,160
Something big sideswiped us.

492
00:28:43,240 --> 00:28:44,280
Sailfish?

493
00:28:45,040 --> 00:28:46,080
Bigger.

494
00:28:46,160 --> 00:28:48,040
Is it the you-know-what?

495
00:28:49,080 --> 00:28:50,840
No, hon, it's not a you-know-what.

496
00:28:50,920 --> 00:28:52,160
Barely any left.

497
00:28:52,480 --> 00:28:54,000
I hate those things.

498
00:28:54,400 --> 00:28:55,920
I wish they never came back.

499
00:28:56,560 --> 00:28:57,760
I just think we should...

500
00:29:08,320 --> 00:29:09,520
Hold on!

501
00:29:16,200 --> 00:29:18,600
- Dad! Dad!
- Teresa!

502
00:29:18,680 --> 00:29:21,040
- Xavier's inside!
- I'll get him. Get to the top.

503
00:29:21,120 --> 00:29:22,200
Get to the top!

504
00:29:24,920 --> 00:29:25,960
Swim!

505
00:29:26,200 --> 00:29:27,200
Xavier!

506
00:29:28,160 --> 00:29:29,296
- It's not opening!
- Let it fill with water!

507
00:29:29,320 --> 00:29:30,376
- Reuben, it won't open!
- Let it fill!

508
00:29:30,400 --> 00:29:32,240
Let it fill,
then you can open the door!

509
00:29:32,320 --> 00:29:34,200
- Why?
- Get the radio! In the red bag!

510
00:29:34,280 --> 00:29:35,720
The red bag! The emergency bag!

511
00:29:35,800 --> 00:29:37,200
- Get up!
- Okay.

512
00:29:41,120 --> 00:29:42,120
Go!

513
00:29:42,200 --> 00:29:43,200
- Where is it?
- Get it!

514
00:29:43,280 --> 00:29:44,416
- I can't find it!
- It's in the bag!

515
00:29:44,440 --> 00:29:46,560
The emergency bag!
The emergency radio!

516
00:29:46,640 --> 00:29:47,640
Okay.

517
00:29:50,440 --> 00:29:51,440
Dad!

518
00:29:51,880 --> 00:29:53,040
Xavier!

519
00:29:53,720 --> 00:29:54,960
Hey! Just get out!

520
00:30:15,160 --> 00:30:17,280
