Dad!

784
00:46:31,120 --> 00:46:32,960
Oh, my god.

785
00:46:45,160 --> 00:46:47,480
What are you doing?
You're heading into the rocks!

786
00:46:47,560 --> 00:46:49,480
I can outrun those things.

787
00:46:49,560 --> 00:46:51,800
The Mosasaur can't go
into shallow water.

788
00:46:54,320 --> 00:46:56,040
Everybody, hold on to something!

789
00:46:59,160 --> 00:47:00,480
I can't move my leg, honey.

790
00:47:03,400 --> 00:47:05,600
If we hit those rocks,
we're gonna wreck.

791
00:47:06,560 --> 00:47:08,080
Tie these to everything you need.

792
00:47:08,440 --> 00:47:09,880
Be ready to jump.

793
00:47:16,480 --> 00:47:17,520
It's fast.

794
00:47:18,680 --> 00:47:20,280
LeClerc, the engine's overheating.

795
00:47:25,840 --> 00:47:28,240
Teresa, get back inside.
Get on the radio.

796
00:47:28,320 --> 00:47:29,856
Mayday three times
and send coordinates. Go!

797
00:47:29,880 --> 00:47:31,296
Three times, send coordinates.
Got it.

798
00:47:31,320 --> 00:47:32,360
Hang on, honey.

799
00:47:34,720 --> 00:47:37,360
Isabella. Isabella, hey, look at me.
It's gonna be okay. Listen.

800
00:47:39,800 --> 00:47:40,880
Mayday! Mayday! Mayday!

801
00:47:40,960 --> 00:47:42,016
- Okay. Hang on.
- Is anybody there?

802
00:47:42,040 --> 00:47:43,096
- Mayday! Mayday!
- Hey... hey. Stop.

803
00:47:43,120 --> 00:47:44,360
- Please! Hey!
- Stop.

804
00:47:44,440 --> 00:47:45,680
Just stop. Stop for a second.

805
00:47:45,760 --> 00:47:46,880
What do you mean, "stop"?

806
00:47:46,960 --> 00:47:48,560
We got to handle this ourselves.

807
00:47:48,640 --> 00:47:49,720
- What?
- This is the...

808
00:47:49,800 --> 00:47:51,760
- This is the protocol.
- Are you crazy?

809
00:47:51,840 --> 00:47:53,256
- No! Mayday. No. No... no.
- Just give me the... Hey.

810
00:47:53,280 --> 00:47:54,920
- No. Hey.
- Hey, Mayday! Mayday!

811
00:47:55,000 --> 00:47:56,360
Back off!

812
00:48:02,240 --> 00:48:03,360
Please help me.

813
00:48:04,160 --> 00:48:06,560
Please. Help me, please.

814
00:48:06,640 --> 00:48:07,840
Please.

815
00:48:07,920 --> 00:48:09,320
Please help me.

816
00:48:09,840 --> 00:48:11,280
Grab my hand, please.

817
00:48:12,040 --> 00:48:13,400
Dad!

818
00:48:16,920 --> 00:48:18,520
Sweetie! Teresa!

819
00:48:18,600 --> 00:48:19,600
No!

820
00:48:20,400 --> 00:48:21,480
Teresa!

821
00:48:23,360 --> 00:48:24,360
Teresa!

822
00:48:28,600 --> 00:48:30,360
Teresa! No!

823
00:48:32,440 --> 00:48:34,240
Man overboard!

824
00:48:35,720 --> 00:48:37,600
Listen to me.
We're going in the water now.

825
00:48:37,680 --> 00:48:40,016
Yes, the boat's gonna crash.
We have to. Your sister's there.

826
00:48:40,040 --> 00:48:41,320
You understand? Hey. Hey.

827
00:48:41,880 --> 00:48:43,560
Hey, I'm here, okay?

828
00:48:43,640 --> 00:48:44,680
All right? I've got you.

829
00:48:44,760 --> 00:48:45,936
- You're all right. Come on.
- Daddy.

830
00:48:45,960 --> 00:48:46,960
Come on!

831
00:48:47,880 --> 00:48:49,640
Get ready. On the count of three.

832
00:48:50,080 --> 00:48:52,480
- One, two, three!
- Hey!

833
00:48:52,560 --> 00:48:54,560
Hey! We need to stick together!

834
00:48:59,040 --> 00:49:00,040
Keep going!

835
00:49:23,040 --> 00:49:24,120
Whoa! Get down!

836
00:49:46,120 --> 00:49:48,240
Zora! It can't go in the shallows!

837
00:49:48,320 --> 00:49:50,040
Jump! Go! Jump!

838
00:50:02,640 --> 00:50:03,680
Told you!

839
00:50:40,560 --> 00:50:41,560
I thought I lost you.

840
00:50:42,000 --> 00:50:43,760
- Are you okay?
- He let me fall.

841
00:50:43,840 --> 00:50:45,000
- Who?
- The guy on the boat.

842
00:50:45,080 --> 00:50:47,240
- He tried to kill me.
- I knew he was creepy!

843
00:50:47,520 --> 00:50:49,200
Teresa? Teresa?

844
00:50:51,400 --> 00:50:52,400
Dad!

845
00:50:58,760 --> 00:51:00,840
- I'm okay. I'm okay.
- Yeah?

846
00:51:00,920 --> 00:51:02,520
I got you. Oh, thank God.

847
00:51:02,600 --> 00:51:04,096
- You all right? Are you good?
- You okay?

848
00:51:04,120 --> 00:51:05,440
Let's get out of the water.

849
00:51:27,920 --> 00:51:28,920
Keep moving!

850
00:51:29,440 --> 00:51:30,760
They're amphibious!

851
00:51:41,160 --> 00:51:42,320
LeClerc, you okay?

852
00:51:46,840 --> 00:51:48,880
Move! Keep going!

853
00:52:00,000 --> 00:52:01,040
We made it.

854
00:52:01,560 --> 00:52:03,520
- I've got it here.
- Do we still have the case?

855
00:52:04,600 --> 00:52:05,720
You got that side?

856
00:52:05,800 --> 00:52:07,440
- We're getting there. Pull.
- Yeah.

857
00:52:07,520 --> 00:52:09,040
Yeah. Come on. Grab it.

858
00:52:09,960 --> 00:52:11,880
Keep going. Yeah. Go on. Grab it.

859
00:52:11,960 --> 00:52:13,120
Keep moving.

860
00:52:13,920 --> 00:52:15,760
It's all right.
Just keep going to the beach.

861
00:52:29,360 --> 00:52:30,400
Nina!

862
00:52:33,320 --> 00:52:35,400
Nina! Nina!

863
00:52:37,400 --> 00:52:38,400
Nina!

864
00:52:39,720 --> 00:52:40,760
Nina!

865
00:52:41,960 --> 00:52:43,000
Nina!

866
00:52:43,080 --> 00:52:44,080
Kincaid!

867
00:52:47,200 --> 00:52:48,280
Nina!

868
00:53:13,480 --> 00:53:14,920
Hey. Hey.

869
00:53:15,000 --> 00:53:16,360
I know. I know.

870
00:53:17,040 --> 00:53:18,240
It's okay, honey.

871
00:53:18,960 --> 00:53:20,280
They said there's a village here.

872
00:53:20,560 --> 00:53:21,840
We'll find it and get help.

873
00:53:22,760 --> 00:53:24,680
All right?
You don't feel like talking?

874
00:53:25,440 --> 00:53:27,000
It's okay, honey. You don't have to.

875
00:53:29,080 --> 00:53:30,160
You'll be okay.

876
00:53:32,520 --> 00:53:34,000
She'll be okay, right?

877
00:53:34,760 --> 00:53:35,760
Yeah.

878
00:53:56,640 --> 00:53:57,720
So, like

879
00:53:58,720 --> 00:54:00,560
when an old person buys a bed

880
00:54:02,680 --> 00:54:06,480
do you think, before they buy it,
they look at it and they go

881
00:54:06,560 --> 00:54:09,720
"Oh, wow, man,
this is... this is my deathbed"?

882
00:54:12,720 --> 00:54:14,320
Because I'm thinking that

883
00:54:16,160 --> 00:54:17,160
right now.

884
00:54:19,320 --> 00:54:20,400
I think we got it.

885
00:54:22,160 --> 00:54:24,080
Come on. Let's go find this village.

886
00:54:28,240 --> 00:54:29,320
Hurry up.

887
00:54:29,400 --> 00:54:31,000
We can't stay here.
They'll come back.

888
00:54:31,080 --> 00:54:33,096
- They're more like mutations.
- What do you mean, "mutations"?

889
00:54:33,120 --> 00:54:35,401
- Abnormalities, deviations.
- I know what the word means.

890
00:54:35,440 --> 00:54:37,320
What does it mean here,
where we are?

891
00:54:37,400 --> 00:54:39,616
- What are you talking about?
- This island that we're on

892
00:54:39,640 --> 00:54:42,120
Mr. Roarke here didn't tell us
everything that we need to know.

893
00:54:42,280 --> 00:54:43,800
Look, dinosaurs are dinosaurs.

894
00:54:43,880 --> 00:54:45,376
- What difference does it make?
- Okay, okay. Fine. Don't tell us.

895
00:54:45,400 --> 00:54:46,496
We could just leave you here.
It's fine.

896
00:54:46,520 --> 00:54:49,760
Fine, so, this island
was a laboratory of sorts.

897
00:54:50,320 --> 00:54:52,520
They conducted
experimental work here.

898
00:54:53,520 --> 00:54:56,080
- What kind of experiments?
- Crossbreeding of species.

899
00:54:56,160 --> 00:54:58,000
The theme park owners
were just responding

900
00:54:58,080 --> 00:54:59,176
to what the audience wanted.

901
00:54:59,200 --> 00:55:01,280
They were tired
of looking at the same old thing.

902
00:55:01,360 --> 00:55:03,320
"Engineered entertainments,"
they called them.

903
00:55:03,640 --> 00:55:05,240
Genetically altered freaks?

904
00:55:05,560 --> 00:55:06,696
Yeah. And you don't want to do that

905
00:55:06,720 --> 00:55:08,240
in the middle
of a theme park, do you?

906
00:55:08,560 --> 00:55:10,640
Ideally, you don't try
weird genetic shit at all.

907
00:55:10,720 --> 00:55:12,560
Well, they learned that the hard way.

908
00:55:12,640 --> 00:55:14,080
Any that were malformed

909
00:55:14,160 --> 00:55:16,800
or just too damn hard
for anybody to look at

910
00:55:17,680 --> 00:55:18,720
they left them here.

911
00:55:21,120 --> 00:55:22,120
Well, that's inhuman.

912
00:55:22,840 --> 00:55:24,040
Why not just euthanize them?

913
00:55:24,120 --> 00:55:27,800
The average cost
of a created species is $72 million.

914
00:55:27,880 --> 00:55:28,880
What would you do?

915
00:55:28,960 --> 00:55:30,176
Kill it and have to tell your bank

916
00:55:30,200 --> 00:55:31,616
or just carry it forward
under R and D?

917
00:55:31,640 --> 00:55:34,480
What would I do with mutant dinosaurs
from an accounting perspective?

918
00:55:34,560 --> 00:55:35,800
Is that really the question?

919
00:55:38,360 --> 00:55:39,880
Can we please just hurry this along?

920
00:55:39,960 --> 00:55:41,440
Everybody, please stay cool.

921
00:55:41,520 --> 00:55:44,320
- Our situation hasn't changed.
- Two of our friends just died.

922
00:55:44,400 --> 00:55:46,136
Clearly, the situation's changed
quite a bit.

923
00:55:46,160 --> 00:55:47,680
Yes, and that's horrible.

924
00:55:47,760 --> 00:55:49,520
But this is where we are now,
desperate

925
00:55:49,600 --> 00:55:51,360
and that's not any different
than before.

926
00:55:51,440 --> 00:55:52,696
We were all desperate to begin with

927
00:55:52,720 --> 00:55:54,280
otherwise,
we wouldn't have come, right?

928
00:55:54,360 --> 00:55:56,720
You, you specialize in a subject
nobody cares about anymore.

929
00:55:56,800 --> 00:55:58,080
You're about to be out of a job.

930
00:55:58,120 --> 00:56:00,600
You need this. I want the money.
You want the money.

931
00:56:00,680 --> 00:56:02,160
Your company wants all the money.

932
00:56:02,240 --> 00:56:03,320
We still have that case.

933
00:56:03,400 --> 00:56:05,200
First sample's in it.
Let's get the other two.

934
00:56:05,280 --> 00:56:06,480
That's a great idea.

935
00:56:07,040 --> 00:56:08,720
We have no weapons, Z.

936
00:56:09,520 --> 00:56:11,000
We never did. I mean, not really.

937
00:56:11,080 --> 00:56:13,640
We had a few toys
that would have made us feel better.

938
00:56:13,720 --> 00:56:15,040
They could have worked or not.

939
00:56:15,120 --> 00:56:17,456
We are where we're supposed to be.
We know what we're supposed to do.

940
00:56:17,480 --> 00:56:19,320
Let's just get what we need
and get out.

941
00:56:19,400 --> 00:56:21,320
Those kids,
the people who went into the ocean

942
00:56:21,400 --> 00:56:22,440
they could still be alive.

943
00:56:22,520 --> 00:56:24,400
I say we find them first,
and then we get out.

944
00:56:24,480 --> 00:56:25,880
Get out how?

945
00:56:25,960 --> 00:56:27,760
Does anyone want to hear
the backup plan?

946
00:56:27,840 --> 00:56:29,320
She has a backup plan?

947
00:56:29,400 --> 00:56:31,320
She doesn't get out of bed
without a backup plan.

948
00:56:35,200 --> 00:56:36,840
I hired an exfil team

949
00:56:36,920 --> 00:56:39,000
to monitor
our boat's radio frequency.

950
00:56:39,080 --> 00:56:41,200
So if we go silent for 24 hours

951
00:56:41,280 --> 00:56:44,440
they'll do a flyby at exactly sunset
on the second night.

952
00:56:44,800 --> 00:56:45,880
But that's tomorrow.

953
00:56:46,960 --> 00:56:48,520
Your plans showed a village complex

954
00:56:48,600 --> 00:56:50,400
on the southwest ridge
with a helipad.

955
00:56:50,480 --> 00:56:51,960
They'll hover
for exactly two minutes.

956
00:56:52,000 --> 00:56:53,656
If no one shows, they'll leave.
But if they see us...

957
00:56:53,680 --> 00:56:56,240
Why only two minutes?
Why don't they just land?

958
00:56:56,320 --> 00:56:57,456
'Cause pilots want to live, too.

959
00:56:57,480 --> 00:56:58,560
Oh, great.

960
00:56:59,040 --> 00:57:01,720
We got to find high ground
before the sun goes down.

961
00:57:08,560 --> 00:57:09,640
We have to go now.

962
00:57:09,720 --> 00:57:11,600
Drop anything
you can't carry all day.

963
00:57:15,520 --> 00:57:16,720
Just try not to die.

964
00:57:37,040 --> 00:57:38,040
Warm.

965
00:57:38,920 --> 00:57:40,400
There's geothermal power.

966
00:57:41,520 --> 00:57:43,440
Must come through these pipes
from hot springs.

967
00:57:45,520 --> 00:57:46,880
It must lead to the village.

968
00:57:48,640 --> 00:57:49,760
Maybe there's a radio?

969
00:57:51,200 --> 00:57:52,880
Great. Yeah.

970
00:57:52,960 --> 00:57:55,160
We use that to get the guy
who tried to kill me.

971
00:57:55,960 --> 00:57:57,360
Or, you know, to get rescued?

972
00:57:57,440 --> 00:57:58,440
Yeah.

973
00:57:58,520 --> 00:58:00,200
Then we'll get the son of a bitch.

974
00:58:00,720 --> 00:58:01,800
Right.

975
00:58:01,880 --> 00:58:04,040
Okay, we follow the pipes
to the village.

976
00:58:04,120 --> 00:58:06,120
Unless somebody's got another idea.

977
00:58:07,400 --> 00:58:08,600
I have some weed.

978
00:58:11,520 --> 00:58:12,520
Might be a little damp

979
00:58:12,600 --> 00:58:15,160
but I feel like
we could just chill here, no?

980
00:58:15,800 --> 00:58:17,120
You don't smoke... Do you smoke?

981
00:58:19,480 --> 00:58:20,480
No?

982
00:58:25,200 --> 00:58:26,200
Okay.

983
00:58:26,600 --> 00:58:27,760
Dad, he's

984
00:58:28,320 --> 00:58:29,720
he's clearly messing with you.

985
00:58:36,280 --> 00:58:37,920
- Yo, help me up?
- Funny.

986
00:58:39,680 --> 00:58:41,400
All right.
No one help me up. That's fine.

987
00:58:59,560 --> 00:59:02,200
Maybe that family will know
to head for the village.

988
00:59:02,280 --> 00:59:03,520
God, I hope so.

989
00:59:07,760 --> 00:59:09,080
How far to the next sample?

990
00:59:09,160 --> 00:59:10,840
Well, according
to the satellite imagery

991
00:59:10,920 --> 00:59:13,160
the Titanosaur herd stays
in the central valley.

992
00:59:14,360 --> 00:59:15,840
We should reach them by dawn.

993
00:59:20,400 --> 00:59:23,040
Be careful where you step.
Something just moved past my leg.

994
00:59:25,160 --> 00:59:28,160
Hey, you want to tell me
how the girl fell over the rail?

995
00:59:28,760 --> 00:59:30,480
The thing hit the boat.
You were there.

996
00:59:31,160 --> 00:59:33,280
So were you, on the bridge,
next to her.

997
00:59:33,360 --> 00:59:35,400
So there was nothing you could do?

998
00:59:36,320 --> 00:59:37,560
What are you implying?

999
00:59:40,440 --> 00:59:42,120
This isn't
your first expedition, huh?

1000
00:59:42,200 --> 00:59:43,880
No, I've been on digs since I was 12.

1001
00:59:44,960 --> 00:59:46,960
I studied under Alan Grant
as a postdoc.

1002
00:59:48,320 --> 00:59:50,520
I suppose you're in this kind
of situation all the time?

1003
00:59:51,040 --> 00:59:52,120
Used to be.

1004
00:59:52,560 --> 00:59:54,640
I hate the jungle.
I try to avoid it now.

1005
00:59:55,240 --> 00:59:56,240
Why is that?

1006
00:59:56,320 --> 00:59:57,960
You can't see three feet
in front of you

1007
00:59:58,040 --> 00:59:59,880
and you always know
you're being stalked.

1008
01:00:00,600 --> 01:00:02,600
And the only place to hide
is underwater.

1009
01:00:04,080 --> 01:00:05,840
I refuse to die in the jungle.

1010
01:00:07,560 --> 01:00:10,680
My dream is I die in a shallow sea,
and I'm buried quickly by silt.

1011
01:00:12,640 --> 01:00:13,640
That's beautiful.

1012
01:00:13,720 --> 01:00:15,800
It's the best chance
of being fossilized that way.

1013
01:00:18,240 --> 01:00:19,400
You're a weirdo.

1014
01:00:20,520 --> 01:00:21,520
Thank you.

1015
01:00:24,920 --> 01:00:25,960
You got to drop this.

1016
01:00:26,040 --> 01:00:29,080
She screamed, I turned around,
and then she was gone.

1017
01:00:29,160 --> 01:00:30,240
Okay. All right.

1018
01:00:30,720 --> 01:00:32,256
If I find out otherwise, though,
we'll leave you here

1019
01:00:32,280 --> 01:00:33,840
and you can rejoin the food chain.

1020
01:00:34,600 --> 01:00:35,960
I'm too smart to die.

1021
01:00:36,280 --> 01:00:37,856
You know, intelligence
is massively overrated

1022
01:00:37,880 --> 01:00:38,880
as an adaptive trait.

1023
01:00:38,960 --> 01:00:40,400
- Oh, yeah?
- Seriously.

1024
01:00:40,480 --> 01:00:41,600
Enlighten us.

1025
01:00:41,960 --> 01:00:44,080
Dinosaurs,
they're pretty dumb, right?

1026
01:00:44,160 --> 01:00:47,000
And yet they've survived
for 167 million years.

1027
01:00:47,080 --> 01:00:50,680
And we Homo sapiens,
geniuses by comparison

1028
01:00:50,760 --> 01:00:53,680
only have about 200,000 years so far.

1029
01:00:53,760 --> 01:00:57,280
But with our huge cranial cavities,
we're so smart

1030
01:00:57,640 --> 01:01:00,160
we already have the capacity
to annihilate ourselves.

1031
01:01:02,160 --> 01:01:04,120
I doubt we make it
to even one million.

1032
01:01:05,080 --> 01:01:06,840
Hold on. Don't we rule the Earth?

1033
01:01:06,920 --> 01:01:08,320
We got to be doing something right.

1034
01:01:08,600 --> 01:01:09,760
We don't rule the Earth.

1035
01:01:10,320 --> 01:01:11,480
We just think we do.

1036
01:01:13,160 --> 01:01:15,040
I mean, sure,
we're changing the environment

1037
01:01:15,120 --> 01:01:17,680
but that makes us the ones
to worry about, not the planet.

1038
01:01:18,320 --> 01:01:20,360
When the Earth gets tired of us,
believe me

1039
01:01:20,440 --> 01:01:23,600
it will shake us off
like a summer cold.

1040
01:01:26,680 --> 01:01:29,000
Of all species
that have existed on Earth

1041
01:01:29,080 --> 01:01:31,720
99.9% of them are now extinct.

